VI've been spending a lot of time
p4
aVtraveling around the world these days,
p5
aVtalking to groups of students and professionals,
p6
aVand everywhere I'm finding that I hear similar themes.
p7
aVOn the one hand, people say,
p8
aV"The time for change is now."
p9
aVThey want to be part of it.
p10
aVThey talk about wanting lives of purpose and greater meaning.
p11
aVBut on the other hand,
p12
aVI hear people talking about fear,
p13
aVa sense of risk-aversion.
p14
aVThey say, "I really want to follow a life of purpose,
p15
aVbut I don't know where to start.
p16
aVI don't want to disappoint my family or friends."
p17
aVI work in global poverty.
p18
aVAnd they say, "I want to work in global poverty,
p19
aVbut what will it mean about my career?
p20
aVWill I be marginalized?
p21
aVWill I not make enough money?
p22
aVWill I never get married or have children?"
p23
aVAnd as a woman who didn't get married until I was a lot older \u2014
p24
aVand I'm glad I waited \u2014
p25
aV(Laughter)
p26
aV\u2014 and has no children,
p27
aVI look at these young people
p28
aVand I say, "Your job is not to be perfect.
p29
aVYour job is only to be human.
p30
aVAnd nothing important happens in life
p31
aVwithout a cost."
p32
aVThese conversations really reflect what's happening
p33
aVat the national and international level.
p34
aVOur leaders and ourselves
p35
aVwant everything,
p36
aVbut we don't talk about the costs.
p37
aVWe don't talk about the sacrifice.
p38
aa(lp39
VOne of my favorite quotes from literature
p40
aVwas written by Tillie Olsen,
p41
aVthe great American writer from the South.
p42
aVIn a short story called "Oh Yes,"
p43
aVshe talks about a white woman in the 1950s
p44
aVwho has a daughter
p45
aVwho befriends a little African American girl,
p46
aVand she looks at her child with a sense of pride,
p47
aVbut she also wonders,
p48
aVwhat price will she pay?
p49
aV"Better immersion
p50
aVthan to live untouched."
p51
aVBut the real question is,
p52
aVwhat is the cost of not daring?
p53
aVWhat is the cost of not trying?
p54
aa(lp55
VI've been so privileged in my life
p56
aVto know extraordinary leaders
p57
aVwho have chosen to live lives of immersion.
p58
aVOne woman I knew who was a fellow
p59
aVat a program that I ran at the Rockefeller Foundation
p60
aVwas named Ingrid Washinawatok.
p61
aVShe was a leader of the Menominee tribe,
p62
aVa Native American peoples.
p63
aVAnd when we would gather as fellows,
p64
aVshe would push us to think about
p65
aVhow the elders in Native American culture
p66
aVmake decisions.
p67
aVAnd she said they would literally visualize
p68
aVthe faces of children
p69
aVfor seven generations into the future,
p70
aVlooking at them from the Earth,
p71
aVand they would look at them, holding them as stewards
p72
aVfor that future.
p73
aVIngrid understood that we are connected to each other,
p74
aVnot only as human beings,
p75
aVbut to every living thing on the planet.
p76
aa(lp77
VAnd tragically, in 1999,
p78
aVwhen she was in Colombia
p79
aVworking with the U'wa people,
p80
aVfocused on preserving their culture and language,
p81
aVshe and two colleagues were abducted
p82
aVand tortured and killed by the FARC.
p83
aVAnd whenever we would gather the fellows after that,
p84
aVwe would leave a chair empty for her spirit.
p85
aVAnd more than a decade later,
p86
aVwhen I talk to NGO fellows,
p87
aVwhether in Trenton, New Jersey or the office of the White House,
p88
aVand we talk about Ingrid,
p89
aVthey all say that they're trying to integrate her wisdom
p90
aVand her spirit
p91
aVand really build on the unfulfilled work
p92
aVof her life's mission.
p93
aVAnd when we think about legacy,
p94
aVI can think of no more powerful one,
p95
aVdespite how short her life was.
