aa(lp97
VAnd I've been touched by Cambodian women \u2014
p98
aVbeautiful women,
p99
aVwomen who held the tradition of the classical dance in Cambodia.
p100
aVAnd I met them in the early '90s.
p101
aVIn the 1970s, under the Pol Pot regime,
p102
aVthe Khmer Rouge killed over a million people,
p103
aVand they focused and targeted the elites and the intellectuals,
p104
aVthe artists, the dancers.
p105
aVAnd at the end of the war,
p106
aVthere were only 30 of these classical dancers still living.
p107
aVAnd the women, who I was so privileged to meet
p108
aVwhen there were three survivors,
p109
aVtold these stories about lying in their cots
p110
aVin the refugee camps.
p111
aVThey said they would try so hard
p112
aVto remember the fragments of the dance,
p113
aVhoping that others were alive and doing the same.
p114
aa(lp115
VAnd one woman stood there with this perfect carriage,
p116
aVher hands at her side,
p117
aVand she talked about
p118
aVthe reunion of the 30 after the war
p119
aVand how extraordinary it was.
p120
aVAnd these big tears fell down her face,
p121
aVbut she never lifted her hands to move them.
p122
aVAnd the women decided that they would train
p123
aVnot the next generation of girls, because they had grown too old already,
p124
aVbut the next generation.
p125
aVAnd I sat there in the studio
p126
aVwatching these women clapping their hands \u2014
p127
aVbeautiful rhythms \u2014
p128
aVas these little fairy pixies
p129
aVwere dancing around them,
p130
aVwearing these beautiful silk colors.
p131
aVAnd I thought, after all this atrocity,
p132
aVthis is how human beings really pray.
p133
aVBecause they're focused on honoring
p134
aVwhat is most beautiful about our past
p135
aVand building it into
p136
aVthe promise of our future.
p137
aVAnd what these women understood
p138
aVis sometimes the most important things that we do
p139
aVand that we spend our time on
p140
aVare those things that we cannot measure.
