aa(lp373
VI had the great honor
p374
aVof working with the child psychologist Dr. Robert Coles,
p375
aVwho stood up for change
p376
aVduring the Civil Rights movement in the United States.
p377
aVAnd he tells this incredible story
p378
aVabout working with a little six-year-old girl named Ruby Bridges,
p379
aVthe first child to desegregate schools in the South \u2014
p380
aVin this case, New Orleans.
p381
aVAnd he said that every day
p382
aVthis six-year-old, dressed in her beautiful dress,
p383
aVwould walk with real grace
p384
aVthrough a phalanx of white people
p385
aVscreaming angrily, calling her a monster,
p386
aVthreatening to poison her \u2014
p387
aVdistorted faces.
p388
aVAnd every day he would watch her,
p389
aVand it looked like she was talking to the people.
p390
aVAnd he would say, "Ruby, what are you saying?"
p391
aVAnd she'd say, "I'm not talking."
p392
aVAnd finally he said, "Ruby, I see that you're talking.
p393
aVWhat are you saying?"
p394
aVAnd she said, "Dr. Coles, I am not talking;
p395
aVI'm praying."
p396
aVAnd he said, "Well, what are you praying?"
p397
aVAnd she said, "I'm praying, 'Father, forgive them,
p398
aVfor they know not what they are doing.'"
p399
aVAt age six,
p400
aVthis child was living a life of immersion,
p401
aVand her family paid a price for it.
p402
aVBut she became part of history
p403
aVand opened up this idea
p404
aVthat all of us should have access to education.
p405
aa(lp406
VMy final story is about a young, beautiful man
p407
aVnamed Josephat Byaruhanga,
p408
aVwho was another Acumen Fund fellow,
p409
aVwho hails from Uganda, a farming community.
p410
aVAnd we placed him in a company in Western Kenya,
p411
aVjust 200 miles away.
p412
aVAnd he said to me at the end of his year,
p413
aV"Jacqueline, it was so humbling,
p414
aVbecause I thought as a farmer and as an African
p415
aVI would understand how to transcend culture.
p416
aVBut especially when I was talking to the African women,
p417
aVI sometimes made these mistakes \u2014
p418
aVit was so hard for me to learn how to listen."
p419
aVAnd he said, "So I conclude that, in many ways,
p420
aVleadership is like a panicle of rice.
p421
aVBecause at the height of the season,
p422
aVat the height of its powers,
p423
aVit's beautiful, it's green, it nourishes the world,
p424
aVit reaches to the heavens."
p425
aVAnd he said, "But right before the harvest,
p426
aVit bends over
p427
aVwith great gratitude and humility
p428
aVto touch the earth from where it came."
p429
aa(lp430
VWe need leaders.
p431
aVWe ourselves need to lead
p432
aVfrom a place that has the audacity
p433
aVto believe we can, ourselves,
p434
aVextend the fundamental assumption
p435
aVthat all men are created equal
p436
aVto every man, woman and child on this planet.
p437
aVAnd we need to have the humility to recognize
p438
aVthat we cannot do it alone.
p439
aVRobert Kennedy once said
p440
aVthat "few of us have the greatness to bend history itself,
p441
aVbut each of us can work
p442
aVto change a small portion of events."
p443
aVAnd it is in the total of all those acts
p444
aVthat the history of this generation will be written.
p445
aVOur lives are so short,
p446
aVand our time on this planet
p447
aVis so precious,
p448
aVand all we have is each other.
p449
aVSo may each of you
p450
aVlive lives of immersion.
p451
aVThey won't necessarily be easy lives,
p452
aVbut in the end, it is all that will sustain us.
p453
aa(lp454
VThank you.
